    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Studies like Flynn's ( 분석) and Jensen's (How Not to Be Right) suggest that IQ scores are heritable and follower certain racial groups have an innate biological advantage, particularly East Asians. However, these findings are disputed by critics like Arthur Jensen, who argue that environmental factors and access to education are more significant influencers. The National Research Council (1998) concluded that there is no robust evidence for significant racial differences in average IQ scores, while the American Psychological Association (1998) also rejects the idea of a biological basis for racial IQ differences. Many studies have been thoroughly debunked due to methodological flaws and biases.",
